<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>Robin Wright is a newspaper and television news correspondent, expert in foreign affairs and diplomacy, especially relating to the Middle East. At various times, she has reported for <title render="italic">The Washington Post</title>, the <title render="italic">Los Angeles Times</title>, <title render="italic">The Sunday Times</title> of London, CBS News and <title render="italic">The Christian Science Monitor</title>. She has also written for The New Yorker, The <title render="italic">Atlantic Monthly</title>, <title render="italic">Foreign Affairs</title>, <title render="italic">Foreign Policy</title>, <title render="italic">The New York Times</title>, <title render="italic">The Times</title> (London), <title render="italic">The Guardian</title> (London), <title render="italic">The International Herald Tribune</title> and many others. She has appeared as guest on network news programs and is a regular panelist on Meet the Press. She is currently (2007) diplomatic correspondent for T<title render="italic">he Washington Post</title>.</p>

<p>Wright has authored several books on the Middle East and Africa, and has taught and lectured on foreign affairs topics. She was the recipient of numerous awards, including a John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation grant.</p>

</bioghist>


<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
<p>The Wright collection is an accumulation of articles and scrapbooks, compiled by Robin Wright's mother, Mrs. L. Hart Wright. The collection also contains a scattering of correspondence, photographs, and biographical information.</p>
</scopecontent>

